<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="exploration-9">
  <title>Exploration 9, due April 5</title>
<handout xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Exploration 9, due April 5</title>

    <p>
        Make sure to familiarize yourself with the Exploration <xref ref="instructions" text="custom"> Instructions </xref> found on the home page.
    </p>

    <p>
        In this exploration, we will investigate least squares solutions and orthogonal projections. 
    </p>

    <problem xml:id="ex-9-pr-1">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Let <m> A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 4 \\ -1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec b = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="ex-9-part-a" workspace="1.5in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Show that the system <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m> is inconsistent.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="ex-9-part-b" workspace="4in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Determine the vector <m>\widehat b = \operatorname{proj}_{\Col(A)}\vec b</m>. Note that the columns of <m>A</m> are <em>not</em> orthogonal.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="ex-9-part-c" workspace="2in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Represent <m>\widehat b</m> as a linear combination of the columns of <m>A</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="ex-9-part-d" workspace="4in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Set up and solve the normal equations for <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m> to find the least square solution. Compare your result to <xref ref="ex-9-part-c" text="custom">Problem 1(c)</xref>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="ex-9-part-e">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Fill in the blanks: When you write <m>\widehat b = \operatorname{proj}_{\Col(A)}\vec b</m> as a linear combination of <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m>, then the <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m> in the linear combination are the entries of <m>\underline{\hspace{4in}}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </problem>


    <problem>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Let <m> A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 4 \\ -1 \amp -4 \\ 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec b = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>. We will repeat similar steps to <xref ref="ex-9-pr-1"/>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task workspace="5in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Determine the vector <m>\widehat b = \operatorname{proj}_{\Col(A)}\vec b</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="2in" xml:id="ex-9-pr-2-b">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Represent <m>\widehat b</m> as a linear combination of the columns of <m>A</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is different about <xref ref="ex-9-pr-2-b" text="custom">Problem 2(b)</xref> compared to <xref ref="ex-9-part-c" text="custom">Problem 1(c)</xref>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="4in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Set up and solve the normal equations for <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m> to find the least square solution. Compare your result to <xref ref="ex-9-pr-2-b" text="custom">Problem 2(b)</xref>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                     Fill in the blanks: If the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly <em>dependent</em>, then there are <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> least squares solutions. This does not mean that there are <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> vectors in <m>\Col(A)</m> which are equally close to <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>, but instead that there are <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> which map to <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </problem>

</handout>
</section>